Incorrect GCC version. The input file was created with the incorrect version of the GNU C compiler. Make sure that the version of the GNU C compiler included in the Automation Studio installation is being used to create the input file.

Cyclic entry point <FunctionName> not allowed. A function in a source file was identified with the prefix attribute "_CYCLIC". This is not allowed for this program type. Remove the "_CYCLIC" attribute from the source code for the program.

Non-cyclic entry point <FunctionName> not allowed. A function in a source file was identified with the prefix attribute "_NONCYCLIC". This is not allowed for this program type. Remove the "_NONCYCLIC" attribute from the source code for the program.

Entry point <FunctionName1> and <FunctionName2> defined multiple times. The entry point has been defined more than once in the program's source files. The entry point is defined by the "_CYCLIC" attribute for cyclic programming or "_NONCYCLIC" for non-cyclic programming. This attribute precedes the corresponding function. Check the source files to see if the "_CYCLIC" or "_NONCYCLIC" attributes occur more than once. If so, delete at the appropriate position.
Input file <Filename> not found. The input file specified in the command line could not be found. Check whether the input file exists. Check the input file's name.

Output file <Filename> cannot be deleted. The old output file that existed before the build cannot be deleted. Check whether the output file is locked or being used by another program. Delete the file.

Output file <Filename> cannot be built. The output file cannot be built in the target directory. Check that the medium where the output file should be built is not write-protected and that it has enough memory available.
Incorrect format for the input file <Filename>. The input file has an invalid format. It must have the output format of the GNU linker. Recompile the project with Automation Studio.

Initialization functions <FunctionName1> and <FunctionName2> defined multiple times. A program's initialization function is run once when the program is installed on Automation Runtime or when Automation Runtime is restarted. This function is identified by the prefix attribute "_INIT". This attribute may only be present once in a program. Check the source files to see if the "_INIT" attribute occurs more than once. If so, delete at the appropriate position.

Deinitialization functions <FunctionName1> and <FunctionName2> defined multiple times. A program's deinitialization function is run once when being cleared on Automation Runtime. This function is identified by the prefix attribute "_EXIT". This attribute may only be present once in a program. Check the source files to see if the "_EXIT" attribute occurs more than once. If so, delete at the appropriate position.

Error creating a section. An error occurred while creating a section in the output file. This is an internal error that cannot be corrected by the user. It's possible that a fatal system bottleneck has occurred that can be corrected by restarting Automation Studio.

No symbol information present for the entry point. No symbol information (debug info) available for the entry point in the input file. The input file was compiled with the option for not generating symbol information. Switch on the option for creating symbol information when compiling the source files into the backend input file. Details about this can be found in the GNU C compiler documentation.

Invalid symbol information. No valid symbol information (debug info) available in the input file. The input file was compiled with the incorrect option for generating symbol information. Switch on the option for creating symbol information when compiling the source files into the backend input file. Details about this can be found in the GNU C compiler documentation.

No fitting symbol found for a GOT entry. A suitable symbol was not found for an entry in the GOT (global offset table). This error should not occur during normal operation and reflects a serious problem in the compilation chain. Please contact B&R Support.

Could not find cyclic entry point for cyclic task. Exactly one cyclic entry point must be defined for cyclic tasks and timer tasks. This definition is made in the source code with the "_CYCLIC" attribute that precedes the function that should be called cyclically by Automation Runtime. Identify a function in the source files an a cyclic entry point by prefixing it with the "_CYCLIC" attribute.

Invalid symbol information. No valid symbol information (debug info) available in the input file. The input file was compiled with the incorrect option for generating symbol information. Could not implement function or function blocks. A function block or function in a library is declared but not being implemented. Implement the function block / function or delete the declaration.
